Anna Wolcott of Windsor CT

1st daughter of Henry and Elizabeth Wolcott of Windsor CT.

(1) Anna Wolcott1 b. ABT 1620 , Somersetshire, England, d. ABT 1701 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesANNA came to America with her sister and younger brother about 1635.
m. 16 OCT 1646 Windsor, Hartford Co., Connecticut, Matthew Griswold, b. 1620 Kenilworth, Warwickshire, England, d. 27 SEP 1698 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
Spouse NotesMATTHEW was a stone cuter. He came to America in 1639. He came to Windsor, Connecticut where he met Anna Wolcott, and then moved to Saybrook, Connecticut as an agent of Lord Fenwich to aid in the construction of a fort and other buildings there. He was given a large land grant there in 1645, marrying Anna the following year. In 1648 he was one of the five men chosen to divide the outlands there. He was the first settler of East Saybrook, after 1667 called Lyme, part of which became Old Lyme in 1855. His property became known as Blackhall, and he was a Lieutenant in the Lyme Train Band. Matthew was one of the signers of the Articles of Seperation. He served as Deputy to the General Court in 1654, 1667, 1678, and 1685, and was also was a Justice of the Peace. He was a lawyer and a mason by trade. He carved many of the early tombstones, including the one for his father-in-law, Henry Wolcott, which still stands. He remained a member of the Saybrook church until his death.
Subtree size: 3071 nodes.
5 children: John, Elizabeth, Matthew, Anna, Sarah.
(2) John Griswold2 (Anna Wolcott1) b. ABT 1651 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 1655 Windsor, Hartford Co., Connecticut.
Subtree size: 1 node.
0 children.
(2) Elizabeth Griswold2 (Anna Wolcott1) b. ABT 1652 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 27 JUL 1727 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
m. 17 OCT 1670 New London, New London Co., Connecticut, John Rogers, b. 1 DEC 1648 New Milford, Litchfield Co., Connecticut, d. 17 OCT 1721 New London, New London Co., Connecticut.
Spouse NotesJOHN founded a religious sect known as the Rogerene Quakers, for which his first wife, Elizabeth Griswold, divorced him in 1676, under pressure from her parents. He vowed to never marry again and wait for her return. He lived as a single man for 25 years, althought he is suspected of having fathered a mulatto son, Adam Rogers. He then married a young housemaid, Mary Rainsford. He refused to be married by a minister or magistrate, and went to a county court session where he announced that he was taking Mary Rainsford as his wife. In 1703 he had the court annul the marriage. John was an ardent abolitionist. He died of smallpox and was buried on his farm, on the bank of the Thames River.

(6) Peter Rogers6 (Grace Rogers5, James Rogers4, John Rogers3, Elizabeth Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 1 JUL 1755 New London, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 5 NOV 1849 Waterloo, Monroe Co., Illinois.
NotesPETER was a fife major in the 4th Regiment, Connecticut Line, 26 Novemer 1776 to 31 December 1779. He was ordered to Washington's Army in Pennsylvania in September 1777 and march in Connecticut Brigade under Gen. McDougall. Engaged in the Battle of Germantown, 4 October 1777. He was in the brigade under Varnum in defence of Fort Mifflin on the Delaware River and was in the Battle of Monmouth, Col. Durkee then commanding the brigade. He was attached to the corps denominated "Washington's Life Guard" according to record of "Connecticut men in the War of the Revolution", Adjunct Generals office, Hartford, Connecticut.

(5) John Rogers5 (John Rogers4, John Rogers3, Elizabeth Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 14 OCT 1761 New London, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 27 MAY 1849 Triangle, Broome Co., New York.
NotesJOHN was a drafted August 1779, at New London, Connecticut. He served in Capt. Richard Deshon's Company, Connecticut State Line until 1782. In 1782 he became a marine on board a private armed ship, the brig, "Marshall". He served on this ship for 40 days. John was one of the pioneers of Broome Co., New York, going there in March 1810, and buying a farm of 134 acres upon which he lived until his death. The land was covered with a heavy growth of pine trees, which he made into lumber, building a saw-mill in 1814 at "Half-way Brook", about five miles from Whitney's Point.

(7) Samuel Keep7 (Samuel Keep6, Sabina Cooley5, Josiah Cooley4, Griswold "Grissell" Beckwith3, Elizabeth Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 6 MAR 1803 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 10 AUG 1830 Baltimore, Baltimore Co., Maryland.
NotesSAMUEL resided at Washington, D.C., where he married a lady of that city on 1 August 1830. On the morning of the 2nd he set out with his wife and two sisters intending to visit his father at Longmeadow. They reached the City Hotel in Baltimore, where on the morning of the 3rd Samuel called for some bottled cider, but through mistake a bottle of corrosive sublimate was drawn by the waiter, a portion of which Sanuel drank, causing immediate vomitting. Physicians were summoned, but moritification took place and he died on 10 August 1830.

(7) John Robinson Keep7 (Samuel Keep6, Sabina Cooley5, Josiah Cooley4, Griswold "Grissell" Beckwith3, Elizabeth Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 22 MAY 1810 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 15 JUN 1885 Hartford, Hartford Co., Connecticut.
NotesJOHN studied at Amherst Academy, and entered Yale University in 1830. He graduated from Yale in 1834. He worked at a school for the deaf and dumb in New York City for a year and then attended Yale Divinity School. He organized a church at Unionville, Connecticut, and in 1842 became pastor of the Congregational Church at Franklin, New York, where he remained two years and then moved to Warren, Connecticut. He retired from the ministry in 1851 due to poor health. He became an instructor at the American Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb at Hartford, Connecticut, for 24 years.

(7) Henry Augustus Keep7 (Heber Keep6, Sabina Cooley5, Josiah Cooley4, Griswold "Grissell" Beckwith3, Elizabeth Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 10 FEB 1811 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 29 DEC 1867 Hartford, Hartford Co., Connecticut.
NotesHENRY was the last of the Keep family to own the old Keep homestead in Longmeadow, having carried on the farm for several years. About 1855 he went to St. Louis, Missouri, and was a partner in a firm that manufactured passenger cars until the break out of the civil war. In 1862 he settle at Hartford, Conn. where he had an iron foundry.

(2) Matthew Griswold2 (Anna Wolcott1) b. 1653 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 13 JAN 1716 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesMATTHEW built an eight room house near his father's home at Black Hall. The house was blown down in a gale in 1815. He was known for his large size and strength. A dispute over land division was resolved by a boxing match, with Matthew representing the town of Lyme. He won, for which he was afterwards called "The Champion".

(3) Matthew Griswold3 (Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 15 SEP 1689 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 1712 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesMATTHEW went to sea, and in Jamaica was pressed into naval service on an English privateer. He was captured by the French and put ashore on the Bay of Hounduras, where he was captured by Spanish Indians, taken 600 miles, and imprisoned. After 6 months he ws taken to Spain. He made his way to Portugal, and from there to Newfoundland. He arrived home where he died at age 24. Probate of his estate mentions his brothers, Samuel, John, George, and Thomas, and sisters, Sarah, Deborah, Mary, and Patience.

(4) Matthew Griswold4 (John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 25 MAR 1714 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 28 APR 1799 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesMATTHEW was a lawyer. He was a Representative to the General Assembly in 1759, and appointed Judge of the Superior Court in 1766. In 1769 he was elected Lieutenant Governor and Chief Justice of Connecticut. He served as Governor of Connecticut from 1784 until 1786, and was President of the state Convention for the adoption of the new Federal Constitution in 1788. He lived in the family home called Black Hall. Her eight daughter were sometimes known as "The Black Hall Boys".

(5) Marian Griswold5 (Matthew Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 17 APR 1750 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 17 JUN 1829 West Springfield, Hampden Co., Massachusetts.
NotesMARIAN was considered a very beautiful, brilliant and outspoken woman. When Justin Ely, who became her 3rd husband, proposed marriage she replied, "Oh, I could not think of burying another husband." She died 12 years after him. Account books of the store and farm at Woodstock, Connecticut begun by her first husband were kept by Marion until 1811.

NotesMARIAN was considered a very beautiful, brilliant and outspoken woman. (6) Elizabeth Griswold6 (John Griswold5, Matthew Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 15 OCT 1778 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 22 JUN 1857 .
m. 28 MAR 1802 New London, New London Co., Connecticut, Jacob Baker Gurley, b. 2 AUG 1771 Mansfield, Tolland Co., Connecticut, d. 24 SEP 1856 New London, New London Co., Connecticut.
Spouse Notes Jacob B. Gurley, Esq., pf New London, Conn., w'as born in the town of Mansfield, Tolland Co., Conn., Aug. 2, 1771 (house shows by photo.). He attended the common schools of the town, and graduated at Dartmouth College in 1793. He was principal or preceptor of the Union School at New London, studied law, and was admitted to the bar in 1797, and became one of the ablest lawyers in New London County. Mr. Gurley was one of the incorporators of the Savings Bank at New London, 1827. He was a public spirited man, and did much for the advancement of the town and city. Soon after the death of his father, he became the owner of the homestead, which he owned the remainder of his life, and rented it during these years to his son-in-law, Mr. An- son Turner. After the death of Mr. Gurley this farm came into the pos- session of his son-in-law, Mr. Charles A. Gurley, who kept it but a few years, and then sold it. This farm had been in the possession of the Gurleys for over a century, and is situated a little south of the old Gurley burying-ground. Charles Griswold Gurley, son of Jacob B. Gurley, Esq., graduated at Yale College, 1827, and died July 4, 1828.

m. John Allen, b. 12 JUN 1763 , d. 31 JUL 1812 Litchfield, Litchfield Co., Connecticut.
Spouse NotesJohn studied law at the Litchfield Law School and was admitted to the bar in 1786. He was a member of the Connecticut House of Representatives 1793-6, and a Representative to Congress 1797-9, a member of the state Council and Supreme Court of Errors 1800-6, after which he practiced law at Litchfield. He was called "Long John Allen", and a poet.

(7) John Allen7 (Ursula McCurdy6, Ursula Griswold5, Matthew Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 1802 , d. 1887 Washington, District of Columbia.
NotesJOHN moved from Litchfield to study law at Cleveland, Ohio, under Judge Samuel Cowles, about 1825. He was admitted to the Cleveland bar, and was the last president of the village council. When Cleveland became a city he was mayor and postmaster, state Senator, Representative to Congress, banker, and railroad director.

(5) Roger Griswold5 (Matthew Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 29 MAR 1762 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 25 OCT 1812 Norwich, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesROGER graduated from Yale College in 1780 and was admitted to the bar in 1783. In 1794 he was elected to Congress to represent Lyme. He served there for ten years. His fight with Representative Matthew Lyon, which led to a physical fight on the floor of the House of Representatives, created quite a stir. He was offered the post of Secretary of War by John Adams, but declined. In 1807 he was appointed a Judge of the Superior Court, and in 1809 was chosen Lieutenant Governor. He was elected Governor of Connecticut in 1811.

(7) Helen Adele "Adele" Griswold7 (Robert Harper Griswold6, Roger Griswold5, Matthew Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 29 MAR 1844 Old Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 27 FEB 1913 Old Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesHELEN and her sister, Florence, lived in the family home after their mother's death, taking in borders and selling plants and vegetables from their garden to make ends meet. In 1899 the artist, Henry Ward Ranger, came to board with them, and he encouraged other artists to stay there and to form an artist's colony at Old Lyme. Shortly after the colony was formed, Adele got tuberculosis and went to live in a sanitarium at Hartford, after which Florence ran the boarding house.

(7) Florence Griswold7 (Robert Harper Griswold6, Roger Griswold5, Matthew Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 25 DEC 1850 Old Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 6 DEC 1937 Old Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesFLORENCE ran the family home as a boarding house for artists and an art gallery after her sister moved to a sanitarium. In 1921 the Lyme Art Association opened a gallery next to her home on land she gave them for this purpose. She was considered a patron of the American Impressionist movement. She became the first manager of the gallery, receiving a percentage of the sales. In 1936 a conservator was appointed for her and her property sold, but she retained life tenancy. The home is now th "Florence Griswold Museum.

(5) Samuel Holden Parsons5 (Phoebe Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 14 MAY 1737 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 17 NOV 1789 Big Beaver River, Beaver Co., Pennsylvania.
NotesSAMUEL graduated at Harvard College, in 1756; and after completing his professional studies in the office of his uncle, Gov. Matthew Griswold, he was admitted to the bar of New
London county, in February, 1759, and settled at Lyme in the practice of law. He was the first lawyer, and the first person to purchase land, in the Western Reserve. He owned 25,000 acres of land there. In 1785 he was appointed Commissioner to treat with the Indians. He became a Judge in the Ohio Territory in 1787, and Chief Justice of the Northwest Territory in 1789. He drowned in the Big Beaver Creek and his body is interred on the south bank of Beaver Creek near its confluence with the Ohio River in Beaver Co., Pennsylvania. His biography was published in "Life and Letters of General Samuel Holden Parsons" by Charles S. Hall, Otsenings Press, Binghampton, New York, 1905.

(6) Phoebe Waite6 (Lucy Marvin Griswold5, Thomas Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 19 JAN 1788 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 1837 .
m. 25 DEC 1809 Saybrook, Middlesex Co., Connecticut, Giles Bishop, b. 1785 , d. 1852 .
Spouse NotesPioneers to Western New York. Went on to Flint, Michigan and, with his two sons, established the first trading post with the Indians in Flint. Learned to talk the Indians'language. Trading post later became a drugstore. Bishop Airport in Flint is on part of the old Bishop farm. The land was donated by Arthur Bishop, a nephew of Giles Bishop, Jr. Arthur was a Flint banker until the age of 90.

Spouse NotesNATHANIEL graduated from Transylvania University in 1806 and studied law. He was admitted to the bar and began practicing law at Ste. Genevieve, Missouri, in 1804 He was appointed Secretary of the Illinois Territory in 1809. In 1816 he was elected Illinois delegate to the U. S. Congress. NotesJOHN grauated from West Point in 1842, and served in the Mexican War. He was appointed Brigidier General of Volunteers in the Union Army in 1861, and commanded the Army of the Mississippi and appointed Major General in 1862. He fought at the Battle of Bull Run. After the war he was assigned to various positions in the West, retiring in 1886. He died in the Old Soldiers Home at Sandusky. He had four children.

(6) Elisha Pope Swift6 (Lucy Eliot5, Clarissa Griswold4, John Griswold3, Matthew Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 12 AUG 1792 Williamstown, Berkshire Co., Massachusetts, d. 3 APR 1865 Pittsburgh, Allegheny Co., Pennsylvania.
NotesELISHA graduated from Williams College, Williamstown, Massachusetts in 1813 and then Princeton Theolgical Seminary. He was ordained as a foreign missionary in 1817 and was minister at First Presbyterian Church, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania from 1835 until his death in 1865. He was the originator of the Western Missionary Society which send out missionaries to the newly opened land in the upper mid-west. Elisha was the founder of Western University and Western Theological Seminary, now Pittsburgh Theological Seminary.

(2) Matthew Griswold2 (Anna Wolcott1) b. 1653 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 13 JAN 1716 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.
NotesMATTHEW built an eight room house near his father's home at Black Hall. The house was blown down in a gale in 1815. He was known for his large size and strength. A dispute over land division was resolved by a boxing match, with Matthew representing the town of Lyme. He won, for which he was afterwards called "The Champion".
m. 30 MAY 1705 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, Mary DeWolf, b. 20 OCT 1656 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 24 OCT 1724 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut.

(6) Phoebe Waite6 (Richard Waite5, Richard Waite4, Mary "Mercy" Bronson3, Anna Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 19 JAN 1788 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 1837 .
m. 25 DEC 1809 Saybrook, Middlesex Co., Connecticut, Giles Bishop, b. 1785 , d. 1852 .
Spouse NotesPioneers to Western New York. Went on to Flint, Michigan and, with his two sons, established the first trading post with the Indians in Flint. Learned to talk the Indians'language. Trading post later became a drugstore. Bishop Airport in Flint is on part of the old Bishop farm. The land was donated by Arthur Bishop, a nephew of Giles Bishop, Jr. Arthur was a Flint banker until the age of 90.

(4) Sarah Waite4 (Mary "Mercy" Bronson3, Anna Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 3 JUL 1717 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 10 MAR 1759 Canaan, Litchfield Co., Connecticut.
m. 7 DEC 1736 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, Simon Tubbs, b. 1711 New Salem, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 19 MAY 1797 Canaan, Litchfield Co., Connecticut.
Spouse NotesSIMON was a member of the church at New Salem in 1748, and later moved to Canaan, Connecticut. He was one of those named on the Indian deed conveying title of the Wyoming Valley to the Susquehanna Company. He was living at Canaan when he conveyed his share in the company to his son, Nathan, in 1777. Nathan conveyed it back to Simon in 1787.
Subtree size: 107 nodes.
12 children: Nathan, Sarah, Phobe, Mary, Simon, John, Joseph, David, Thomas, Simon, Elizabeth, Andrew.
(5) Nathan Tubbs5 (Sarah Waite4, Mary "Mercy" Bronson3, Anna Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 20 MAR 1738 New Salem, New London Co., Connecticut, d. ABT 1798 Huntington Township, Luzerne Co., Pennsylvania.
NotesNATHAN enlisted 12 April 1759, in Capt. Tarball Whitney's 10th Company, Col. David Wooster's Regiment, for service in the French and Indian War. He settled at Norfolk, Connecticut before 1764. He enlisted 5 March 1777 in Capt. Titus Watson's Co., Col. Heman Swift's 7th Regiment of the Connecticut Continental Line in the American Revolution. He was at Camp Peekskill, New York in the spring of 1777. In September 1777, the regiment under the command of Gen. McDougall, was order to join Gen. Washington in Pennsylvania. It was at Germantown 4 October 1777, and at Valley Forge in the winter of 1777-8. He took part in the battle of Monmouth, New Jersey 28 June 1778. In 1790 he was living at Huntington Valley, Pennsylvania. He was living at Huntington in 1798, when he conveyed 300 acres to his sons, Nathan and Simon.
m. BEF 1763 Elizabeth Earle, b. 1732 , d. 1814 .

(7) John Tuttle Andrews7 (Ichabod Andrews6, Prudence Pinny Stanley5, Abraham Stanley4, Elizabeth Bronson3, Anna Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 29 MAY 1803 Schoharie Creek, Greene Co., New York, d. 11 JUN 1894 Dundee, Yates Co., New York.
NotesJOHN taught school for several years and then entered a merchantile business at Irelandville and Watkins, New York. He was a Justice of the Peace, and sheriff of Steuben County, New York 1836-7. He was elected to Congress on the Democratic ticket 1837-9. He then moved to Dunde, New York, and was a merchant there 1866-77. In 1880 he was a retired merchant at Dundee, New York, living with niece Pheba E. Thomas.

m. 12 APR 1832 Dundee, Yates Co., New York, John Tuttle Andrews, b. 29 MAY 1803 Schoharie Creek, Greene Co., New York, d. 11 JUN 1894 Dundee, Yates Co., New York.
Spouse NotesJOHN taught school for several years and then entered a merchantile business at Irelandville and Watkins, New York. He was a Justice of the Peace, and sheriff of Steuben County, New York 1836-7. He was elected to Congress on the Democratic ticket 1837-9. He then moved to Dunde, New York, and was a merchant there 1866-77. In 1880 he was a retired merchant at Dundee, New York, living with niece Pheba E. Thomas.

(2) Sarah Griswold2 (Anna Wolcott1) b. 25 SEP 1657 Lyme, New London Co., Connecticut, d. 12 SEP 1690 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts.
m. 11 SEP 1677 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, Thomas Colton, b. 1 MAY 1651 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 30 SEP 1728 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts.
Spouse NotesTHOMAS was a Captain in the French and Indian Wars. In 1693 the town of Springfield sent him and Luke Hitchcock to "the Bay" to procure a minister. Springfield, Long-Meadow, Septemb. 30, 1728. This day dy'd here, Capt. Thomas COLTON, (after a considerable confinement) in the 7th years of his age. He was a gallant soldier, did great service in the Indian War. He was a loving husband, a tender parent, a hearty friend, and an eminent Christian, of great faith, patience, & hope, was most ready and willing to meet death, "being through the Grace of Christ possest with a full perswation of the favour of God." His death was (as he had oft desired of God it might be) most easy; he dyed in his chair, without a groan or struggle. Psal. 12. 1. Help Lord, for the godly man ceaseth, for the faithful sail from among the children of men.

m. 27 FEB 1695 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, Samuel Keep, b. 22 AUG 1670 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 23 AUG 1755 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts.
Spouse NotesSAMUEL and his two sisters were raised by their grandmother Leonard after their parents were killed by Indians. Later he lived with his uncle, Samuel Bliss. He was chosen to make the first survey of the outlying areas of Springfield, Massachusetts. Samuel assigned his son, John, then aged 18, to make the survery of the Monson area in 1715.

(5) Jabez Keep5 (John Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 2 MAR 1728 Brimfield, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 17 SEP 1805 Homer, Cortland Co., New York.
NotesJABEZ served as a Corporal in Capt. Daniel Burt's Company in the French and Indian War, from 30 March 1755 to 3 January 1756. His father John Keep deeded some land at Brimfield to him in June, 1755, and in 1759 he purchased other land from the estate of Adonijah King. He was elected Assessor of Brimfield in 1760. After Monson was created a precinct he served as Selectman in 1767 and 1769. Jabez and his wife, Sarah, were first cousins. He is considered by the DAR to have performed "patriotic service" during the Revolution.

NotesLAMIRA and her husband purchased a home in 1854. It became a dairy farm, and had several small rock quarries. In 1856, Marcus conveyed the home to his nephew, Edward Keep, as his own children had all predeceased him. Marcus' estate was divided between his nephew and neice, Edward and Mary Keep, who he had raised. The home is now the Keep Homestead Museum.

(5) Caleb Keep5 (John Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 10 DEC 1741 Brimfield, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 6 OCT 1816 Homer, Cortland Co., New York.
NotesCALEB served as a Sergeant in Capt. Freeborn Moulton's Company, Col. Danielson's Regiment, Massachusetts militia, which marched at the Lexington alarm of 19 April 1775, from Monson to Cambridge. He was a Lieutenant in Capt. Joseph Thompsons' Company, Col. Danielson's Regiment, 1 August 1775 and served 3 months, 15 days. He was at Roxbury, 27 May 1775. Caleb was a Captain in Col. Shepard's Regiment from 1 January 1777 to 13 April 1778 and was at the battle of Saratoga. He was a Captain in Col. Israel Chapin's Regiment, 15 October 1779 to 21 November 1779. He was also Captain of the 9th Company, 1st Regiment, Hampshire County Militia under Col. Gideon Burt on 1 July 1781. After the war he was a selectman and a Representative to the General Court.
m. 26 APR 1770 Springfield, Hampshire Co., Massachusetts, Mary "Mercy" Stebbins, b. 12 FEB 1747 Wilbraham, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 5 MAY 1837 Homer, Cortland Co., New York.
Subtree size: 47 nodes.

NotesALBERT came from Fredonia to Whitewater with his brother, Henry, in 1847. He formed a parnership with Philander Keep to operate a retail business. In 1851 Peek & Keep entered the wholsale dry goods trade at Chicago. In 1856 Albert turned to real estate, and was hired to secure a right of way through Chicago for the Chicago & Nothwestern Railroad. He became a director of the railroad in 1865, and became President of the Chicago & Northwestern Railroad in 1883.

(7) Samuel Keep7 (Samuel Keep6, Samuel Keep5, Samuel Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 6 MAR 1803 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 10 AUG 1830 Baltimore, Baltimore Co., Maryland.
NotesSAMUEL resided at Washington, D.C., where he married a lady of that city on 1 August 1830. On the morning of the 2nd he set out with his wife and two sisters intending to visit his father at Longmeadow. They reached the City Hotel in Baltimore, where on the morning of the 3rd Samuel called for some bottled cider, but through mistake a bottle of corrosive sublimate was drawn by the waiter, a portion of which Sanuel drank, causing immediate vomitting. Physicians were summoned, but moritification took place and he died on 10 August 1830.

(7) John Robinson Keep7 (Samuel Keep6, Samuel Keep5, Samuel Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 22 MAY 1810 Longmeadow, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 15 JUN 1885 Hartford, Hartford Co., Connecticut.
NotesJOHN studied at Amherst Academy, and entered Yale University in 1830. He graduated from Yale in 1834. He worked at a school for the deaf and dumb in New York City for a year and then attended Yale Divinity School. He organized a church at Unionville, Connecticut, and in 1842 became pastor of the Congregational Church at Franklin, New York, where he remained two years and then moved to Warren, Connecticut. He retired from the ministry in 1851 due to poor health. He became an instructor at the American Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb at Hartford, Connecticut, for 24 years.

(5) Sarah Chandler5 (Sarah Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 12 AUG 1741 Enfield, Hartford Co., Connecticut, d. 8 OCT 1819 Homer, Cortland Co., New York.
m. Jabez Keep, b. 2 MAR 1728 Brimfield, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 17 SEP 1805 Homer, Cortland Co., New York.
Spouse NotesJABEZ served as a Corporal in Capt. Daniel Burt's Company in the French and Indian War, from 30 March 1755 to 3 January 1756. His father John Keep deeded some land at Brimfield to him in June, 1755, and in 1759 he purchased other land from the estate of Adonijah King. He was elected Assessor of Brimfield in 1760. After Monson was created a precinct he served as Selectman in 1767 and 1769. Jabez and his wife, Sarah, were first cousins. He is considered by the DAR to have performed "patriotic service" during the Revolution.

(7) Redfield Proctor7 (Jabez Proctor6, Mary Keep5, Jabez Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 1 JUN 1831 Cavendish, Windsor Co., Vermont, d. .
NotesRedfield graduated from Dartmouth College and the Albany Law School. He served as Lt. and Quartermaster of the 3rd, Maj. of the 5th and Col. of the 15th Regiments of Vermont Volunteers during the Civil War.
He was a memer of the Vermont house of representatives in 1867,1868 and 1888; a member of the State Senate and president pro-term of the body in 1864 and 1875; was Lt. Gov. from 1876 to 1878; Governor from 1878 to 1880; Secretary of War in the Cabinet of Benjamin Harrison from March 1889 to November 1891, when he resigned from the Cabinet to serve as Senator in Congress from Vermont.
In February of 1898 he made a visit to Cuba and on his return made a strong speech in the Senate on Cuban matters.

(5) Jonathan Keep5 (Jabez Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 7 AUG 1745 Westford, Middlesex Co., Massachusetts, d. Pepperell, Middlesex Co., Massachusetts.
NotesJONATHAN was a blacksmith and a lawyer. For the greater part of his life he was also a tavernkeeper. In 1774 and 1776 he was a Selectman of Westford and in 1776 was one of four who were hired "for numbering the people in this town. On July 14, 1780, he was commissioned as First Lieutenant in the 1st Company, 6th Regiment, Middlesex county Militia. In 1782 and 1783 he was Town Treasurer of Groton, and Town Clerk of Groton in 1784. In 1785 he returned to Westford. He was chosen to represent Westford at the state convention to consider the Federal Constitution in 1788. Jonathan Keep voted against the ratification of the Constitution. He was again a Selectman in Westford in 1787 and 1788, and was clerk that board from 1787 to 1789. He moved back to Groton in 1790, where he remained till 1797, when he sold his pew in the church and went to Townsend, where he was Selectman in 1802. Afterward he became a resident of Pepperell. He is sometimes given the militery rank of Captain, but there is apparently no evidence for this.
m. 26 JUL 1769 Hannah Hildreth, b. 5 DEC 1750 Westford, Middlesex Co., Massachusetts, d. 5 FEB 1815 Pepperell, Middlesex Co., Massachusetts.

(5) Jonathan Keep5 (Jabez Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 7 AUG 1745 Westford, Middlesex Co., Massachusetts, d. Pepperell, Middlesex Co., Massachusetts.
NotesJONATHAN was a blacksmith and a lawyer. For the greater part of his life he was also a tavernkeeper. In 1774 and 1776 he was a Selectman of Westford and in 1776 was one of four who were hired "for numbering the people in this town. On July 14, 1780, he was commissioned as First Lieutenant in the 1st Company, 6th Regiment, Middlesex county Militia. In 1782 and 1783 he was Town Treasurer of Groton, and Town Clerk of Groton in 1784. In 1785 he returned to Westford. He was chosen to represent Westford at the state convention to consider the Federal Constitution in 1788. Jonathan Keep voted against the ratification of the Constitution. He was again a Selectman in Westford in 1787 and 1788, and was clerk that board from 1787 to 1789. He moved back to Groton in 1790, where he remained till 1797, when he sold his pew in the church and went to Townsend, where he was Selectman in 1802. Afterward he became a resident of Pepperell. He is sometimes given the militery rank of Captain, but there is apparently no evidence for this.
m. 19 JAN 1816 Pepperell, Middlesex Co., Massachusetts, Ruth Scott, b. , d. .

(7) Aurelia P. Belcher7 (Olive Keep6, John Keep5, Jabez Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 2 JAN 1818 Chicopee Falls, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, d. 1864 Milwaukee, Milwaukee Co., Wisconsin.
m. 1844 Chicopee Falls, Hampden Co., Massachusetts, Arthur Mac Arthur, b. 26 JAN 1815 Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland, d. 24 AUG 1896 Atlantic City, Atlantic Co., New Jersey.
Spouse NotesArthur MacArthur, Sr. (January 26, 1815 - August 26, 1896) was an American lawyer, judge, and politician who served as the acting governor of Wisconsin for four brief days in 1856, in the midst of an election scandal. MacArthur was born in Glasgow, Scotland, the descendant of Highlander nobility through his father, who had died just seven days before his birth in 1815. His mother remarried and moved the family to Uxbridge, Massachusetts in 1828. MacArthur attended school briefly at Wesleyan College in Connecticut, but dropped out to help his family through a severe economic depression in 1837. He worked as a law clerk in Boston and then New York, and was admitted to the New York bar in 1841. Around 1844, he married Aurelia Belcher (1819 - 1864), the daughter of a wealthy industrialist. With the help of his father-in-law, MacArthur established a very successful legal practice in Springfield. Differences in politics between the immigrant Democrat MacArthur and his conservative Whig in-laws soon led him to move his family from their influence. He set up a law office in New York City in 1845, and finally settled in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, in 1849. MacArthur quickly befriended the powerful in his new home state, and was elected as the city attorney of Milwaukee in 1851. In 1855, he was offered the Democratic nomination for lieutenant governor, as running mate to the incumbent, William A. Barstow. The election ended in scandal. Though Barstow was initially declared winner by a mere 157 votes, the result was challenged as a fraud by Barstow's opponent, the Republican Coles Bashford, and it was substantiated that election returns had been forged from non-existent precincts. Barstow kept hold of the office anyway, and as the rivals' militia forces converged on the state capital of Madison threatening to start a civil war, Barstow and MacArthur were inaugurated publicly on January 7, 1856. Despite his promises to hold onto the office at all costs, Barstow eventually realized that he was fighting a losing battle both legally and in public opinion, and resigned on March 21, 1856, four days before the Wisconsin Supreme Court resolved the controversy in favor of Bashford. MacArthur became acting governor upon Barstow's resignation and initially repeated his predecessor's resolve to remain in office. On March 25, however, when confronted face to face with a threat to use force from Bashford, a county sheriff, and a throng of Bashford's followers, MacArthur and his supporters vacated the Capitol. MacArthur finished his term as lieutenant governor, leaving office in 1857. The election scandal somehow left MacArthur's reputation relatively unscathed, and he won election for two terms as a judge on the Wisconsin Second Judicial Circuit, from 1857 until 1869. In 1870, President Grant appointed MacArthur as an associate justice on the Supreme Court of the District of Columbia,a position that he held until his retirement in 1887. MacArthur spent his remaining years in Washington moving in high society, accepting speaking engagements, and writing books. He died in Atlantic City, New Jersey and was buried in Rock Creek Cemetery in Washington. MacArthur had two sons, Frank, and famed General Arthur MacArthur, Jr., for whom he had first secured an appointment to West Point Military Academy and then as a first lieutenant in the 24th regiment of Wisconsin Volunteers. Arthur Jr. was himself the father of a general of even greater fame, the World War II commander, Douglas MacArthur.

(7) Henry Keep7 (Heman Chandler Keep6, Matthew Keep5, Matthew Keep4, Sarah Colton3, Sarah Griswold2, Anna Wolcott1) b. 22 JUN 1818 Adams, Jefferson Co., New York, d. 30 JUL 1869 New York City, New York.
NotesHENRY's father died when he was young, leaving the family without money. Henry was apprenticed to a farmer, but ran away to Rochester in 1817 where he found work on the Erie Canal. He saved his money and invested in depreciated currency in 1837, getting a large profit. Then he speculated in Canadian banknotes and made more money. He established a bank at Watertown, New York, and expanded to several smaller towns. In 1850 he moved to New York City and began speculating on Wall Street, investing in railroad stocks. He was Treasurer of the MIchigan Southern Railroad, 1861-1863 and in 1866 President of the New York Central Railroad. From June 1868, until his death, he was president of the Chicago and Northwestern Railorad, controlling manager of the Northern Indiana and the Cleveland and Toledo Railroad. He was a temperate, moral and prudent man and his business sagacity was such that he had the confidence of all the Wall Street capitalists of his time. By his industry, perseverance and good judgement he accumulated a fortune of $4,000,000.
m. Emma Woodruff, b. , d. 1891 .

NotesMATTHEW was at the Lexington Alarm as a Corporal in Maj. Andrew Colton's Co, which marched from Springfield 20 April 1775. He served as a Private in Capt. Spouse NotesJOSEPH was of Hatfield, Massachusetts. In 1763 he and his son, Joseph Billings Jr., and others petitioned the Governor of New Hampshire for a grant of land there. The grant of land at Swanton, New Hampshire, was issued and Joseph and his son's names appear as grentees.
